communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[During 2013, Zimbabwe submitted immediate and follow-up reports to the OIE regarding 2 foot and mouth disease (FMD) events. In those cases, FMD serotypes SAT-2 and SAT-3 were identified.

Where SAT-2 was identified, 8 outbreaks were reported, 6 of which were located in the Masvingo region. The source of infection was also determined to be contact with wild species and illegal movement of animals. The complete report and map are available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000014210_20140113_141425.pdf.

For the event where SAT-3 was identified, the source of infection was due to the illegal movement of animals. See complete report at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000014209_20140113_141108.pdf.

During 2012, Zimbabwe reported 15 outbreaks of FMD serotype SAT-2. According to these reports 238 935 bovines were vaccinated as a response to the outbreak. This information is available in the annual report sent to the OIE in 2012; see http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/semestrial/review?year=2012&semester=0&wild=0&country=ZWE&this_country_code=ZWE&detailed=1.

Although many species of cloven-hoofed wildlife may become infected, African buffalo (_Syncerus caffer_) are the only wildlife species which plays a significant role in the epidemiology of FMD. Spillover of infection into livestock occurs periodically. See http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.01.05_FMD.pdf and http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Animal_Health_in_the_World/docs/pdf/Disease_cards/FOOT_AND_MOUTH_DISEASE.pdf. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2484074,10604.]
